Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
Subject: Re: Creeping featuritis (post --rant --flame)
From: haley@scws14.harvard.edu (Elizabeth Haley)
Date: 2 Dec 93 03:12:24 GMT

djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein) writes:

>> Moreover, the user interface is now *much* more complex.

>Red herring. You really think it's the job of every single software tool
>to provide the user interface du jour? I don't. Make a tar wrapper if 
>you're desperate.

I would suggest that MIB is not at all desparate about this, since the
solution, for him and other, already exists. Why should he change
anything if he doesn't want to?
I would also suggest that having a simpler user interface is fairly
important, so long as the features being added are appropriate.

>> file can be split across the boundary

>The user can replace a big file FOO with a whole bunch of little files
>FOO/0 FOO/32768 etc. (the numbers indicating byte markers). Why, oh why, 
>if this feature _had_ to be in tar, wasn't it implemented just like 
>this?

Because the feature as you suggest it is annoying and inefficient. If
I am archiving things that I know are larger than the media I am
writing to, I don't particularly want to make a bunch of small chunks,
and attempt to figure out where the tape is going to end in relation to
the chunks when the program can figure out where it ends on the fly
and make just one break in just one file.

Maybe I am just not as clever as you, but I fail to understand how
this would be a great deal more efficient or coherent than the way it
is being done now.

But Fortunately, you're in luck!!! This code is under the GPL, so you
can take it, rip out the multi-volume stuff, and put in the splitter
support, and release it! 

I know I'll be looking forward to it!
--
Hacksaw

