Crossposted-To: gnu.misc.discuss
From: keith@ksmith.com (Keith Smith)
Subject: Re: Creeping featuritis (post --rant --flame)
Date: Wed, 01 Dec 93 16:05:11 GMT

In article <1993Nov3004.29.31.28914@silverton.berkeley.edu>,
D. J. Bernstein <djb@silverton.berkeley.edu> wrote:

["rants" about tar & cpio]

>This shortsightedness means that you end up writing multi-volume support 
>for tar and writing it _again_ for cpio. Duplicate. Duplicate. Bad. Bad.
>
>You have to extend tar. Fine. It wasn't perfect. Why don't you think for
>a few minutes and come up with a flexible extension that _lets_ you keep
>multi-volume support in a separate program?

Yuk Foo.

This is a typical Unix Laziness.  It seems to me were talking about a
Statically liked binary of less than 100K in either case.  The
intelligent thing to do would be to COMBINE the programs into one.  I
mean face it.  Were talking about some pretty simple concepts with
different options, but basically they are dumping information onto some
medium in a combined format.  What other types of tools will need
"Multi-Volume" support pray tell?  I'd like to see a SINGLE binary hard
linked to pax,tar,cpio, and whatever else that handles _all_ of the
issues that may come up, INCLUDING compression & the like.

There is also no law that says a SINGLE binary cannot call
(transparently) other system routines, NOR are there any laws against
building archive routine LIBRARIES callable from 'C' either.  The only
problem with the former is that a single binary may not be distributable
on it's own and the latter may swell your binaries slightly.  I'd still
bet a single binary for _all_ exchange formats would take less _space_
than multiple binaries with dependent filters and such.

Finally there is the issue of maintenance.  It is a pain in the ass to
maintain multiple binaries, ESPECIALLY when there are defined
interactions between them (Can you say libc.so.XXXX).  A slight change
in one section of your pipe and _NOTHING_ works anymore.  Swell.

Here is what I would like to see:

C library functions for gzip style compression, perhaps as a stream
filter:

FILE *f;

FILE gzip_fopen(char *name, char *mode);
int gzip_fclose(FILE *stream);

and function for memory block compression too:

/* returns new size */
long gzip_mem(void *target, static void *block, long *size);

Once the _library_ is standardized you eliminate duplicate coding
efforts, and changes to non-shared libraries won't affect already
existing binaries.

Hmmm,  Maybe something _I_ could even accomplish.
-- 
Keith Smith          keith@ksmith.com              5719 Archer Rd.
Digital Designs      BBS 1-919-423-4216            Hope Mills, NC 28348-2201
Somewhere in the Styx of North Carolina ...

