Crossposted-To: comp.sys.amiga.tech,comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware.chips,comp.periphs.scsi
From: drew@cs.colorado.edu (Drew Eckhardt)
Subject: Do any PC or Amiga SCSI adapters use the  NCR53c700 (nee 710, etc)
Date: Thu, 2 Dec 1993 06:26:27 GMT

I'm currently developing a Linux SCSI driver for the NCR53c700/800
series of SCSI chips.  

For some of the features I'll be supporting (ie, different synchronous 
speeds used for different targets), the code for the NCR53c700 and 
NCR53c700-66 is hackish and I don't like it (Ie, I need to halt the 
SCSI SCRIPTS(tm) processor, interrupt the host processor, have the host 
processor twiddle bits, and restart the script).  

The newer chips (the NCR53c710, 720, 810, and 820) have a more 
reasonable microcontroller on board, with an ALU, the ability to read and 
write chip registers, etc. which will let me handle most of the ugly 
situations (the different synchronous settings for different targets, 
SAVE POINTERS / RESTORE DATA POINTER messages, etc) within my SCSI SCRIPTs
(tm). 

So, If there are PC or Amiga SCSI boards using the NCR53c700 or NCR53c700-66
rather than the newer chips, I'll make an effort to provide alternate SCSI 
SCRIPTS (tm) for those chips and to keep the extra intelligence in the Linux 
code needed to deal with them.

If not, I won't waste any more time keeping my code compatable with the 
NCR53c700 and NCR53c700-66.


