From: becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker)
Subject: Re: Any idea how to AUTOIRQ a parallel port?
Date: Wed, 1 Dec 1993 05:25:51 GMT

In article <davem.754663422@extro.ucc.su.oz.au>,
David Monro <davem@extro.ucc.su.OZ.AU> wrote:
>I know, sounds crazy, but I have several machines with different setups,
>and it is a pain to have to hack lp.h and build separate kernels for each
>one. (For example on one machine I have lp0 on irq 7, lp2 on irq5, but on
>another I have lp1 on irq 7 and lp2 on irq12. And yes, it has to be that
>way. It is also subject to change quite often when testing things.)

It's possible to autoIRQ on a parallel port only if you can control what's
hooked up to it.  To sense the interrupt line you must "twinkle" the interrupt
and see which line the interrupt comes in on.  

On the ISA bus undriven interrupt lines float high, and interrupts occur on a
low-to-high transition.  Interrupt lines can be "shared" (in a mutually
exclusive sense) by having the device isolate it's interrupt input from the
with a "line driver".

With some devices you can clear the interrupt sources, enable the interrupt
line driver to drive the IRQ line low, and then disable the interrupt line
driver to let the IRQ line float high and generate an interrupt.  But for this
to work you need some way to clear the interrupt source, but you can't
reliably do that unless you know something about what's hooked up to the
printer port.

For a concrete example, my 'ATP' pocket ethernet adaptor driver can autoIRQ
the printer port but that same code wouldn't be reliable without the device
hooked up.  (You could still try it of course, but the driver would have to
be ready to fall back to polled-I/O if it failed.)

-- 

Donald Becker                                          becker@super.org
IDA Supercomputing Research Center
17100 Science Drive, Bowie MD 20715                        301-805-7482

