From: becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker)
Subject: Re: Auto port detection for a 3c501?
Date: Wed, 1 Dec 1993 14:32:24 GMT

In article <1993Dec1.083332.18875@dxcern.cern.ch>,
Gerrit Nieuwenhuizen <nieuwhzn@dxgsia.cern.ch> wrote:
>Does this mean that the 3c501 is supported by Linux?
>When I looked in the supported hardware I saw that only
>its 16bit brother (3c503 or similar) was in the kernel
>device drivers.

The 3c503 would be insulted to be called the brother of the 3c501.  While
the DP8390 controller used on the 3c503 board has a few bugs, the 3c501 is
more like a bug surrounded by a board.  And the worst part is that 3Com
products are built so well that the 3c501 boards _just_won't_die_.

An amusing story: locally someone has a "power machine".  It's a EISA DX2-66
with 64M of memory, a SCSI-2 controller, a huge disk, a big monitor, etc.
(Just the memory for this machine costs significantly more than the fastest
Linux box I work with.)  What did they use for the network connection?  A
3c501 that was sitting around.  That's like putting $30 tires on a Ferrari.
(Of course, this box is hardly ever used.)


